ep it short and use it to update the world model. Helpful optional prefixes are `World model:`, `Goal model:`, `Action model:`, `Recent findings:`, `Open questions:`, `Plan:`, and `Cross-level notes:`.\nWhen calling `python`, emit exactly the tool-call format shown elsewhere in this prompt for this model. Use only that format; do not add markdown fences, prose wrappers, or alternate tool-call syntax. Do not quote or place tool-call markup inside explanatory text; when you decide to call the tool, emit the tool call itself.\nIf you use MOUSE, include integer row and col arguments.\nEFFICIENCY BUDGET \u2014 your score on each level is (baseline_actions / your_actions)^2, so every wasted action costs you quadratically.\nLevel 2: you have used 142 actions; a strong score needs about 58 or fewer. You are 2.4x over the target.\nIf you are not steadily making progress toward the level goal, commit to your single best hypothesis and the shortest sequence that tests it \u2014 do not exhaustively scan rows/columns or enumerate every option. Test one idea, read the result, then decide.", "kind": "tool", "inContext": true}, {"label": "THINKING", "content": "After RIGHTx4, SPACE:\n- Red: (16-19, 8-27) - a simple rectangle now!\n- Blue: (20-23, 4-23)\nThe red block is now a simple rectangle at (16-19, 8-27). The blue is at (20-23, 4-23), which is where the bottom part of the red block was.\nSo the SPACE caused the two parts of the red block to merge into one rectangle, and the blue took the position of the bottom part.\nNow I have a single red block at (16-19, 8-27) and the blue at (20-23, 4-23).\nThis is similar to the initial state, but the red block is wider (8-27 instead of 8-19).\nLet me think about what to do next. The blue is at (20-23, 4-23), and the red is at (16-19, 8-27).\nIf I move UP, the blue would move to (16-19, 4-23), which overlaps with the red at cols 8-23.\nThen SPACE might cause the red to shrink or split.\nLet me try: UP 2, SPACE. This would put the blue at 